Unai Emery has been sacked as Arsenal manager after 18 months in charge, according to BBC. The embattled manager has been replaced by his assistant Freddie Ljumberg on temporary basis though questions that have dominate media are focussing on Emery's heir. Several coaches have been linked with Arsenal including Wolves’ Nuno Espirito Santo as a replacement of Emery. The Spaniard, who previously led Paris St-Germain to the French league title and won three Europa Leagues with Sevilla, was appointed Gunners boss in May 2018, succeeding Arsene Wenger. Arsenal management said on Tuesday that it has decided to take the decision to to “results and performances not being at the level required". The Gunners have not won in seven games and lost 2-1 at Emirates to Eintracht Frankfurt in the Europa League on Thursday night. According to BBCSport, it is the Gunners worst competitive run without a victory since February 1992, which was eight games under George Graham.